title: For Sale:  ATI Calvary SX: Engraved O/U 12Ga, 28" (NIB)
postcontent:
O/U .12GA O/U SHOTGUN
Yes, this shotgun looks and performs like a $2000+ shotgun, but look at the price. American Tactical Importers (ATI) imports the Calvary shotguns from Turkey and some believe they are made by Yildiz, one of the world's best shotgun manufacturers and sub-contract to big names, like Weatherby. The Turkish economy has seen better days and the skilled workers aren't paid very much. The cost in production is directly proportional to the price tag. Thus, we have a low-priced shotgun that has the looks, performance and dependability of the higher priced guns. Just compare the description items below (even has auto ejectors!), along with the price, with any O/U shotgun and you'll understand why it's so hard to find or keep one in stock. Sorry, but I have the last ONE from my wholesalers. My Cousin, Ronnie or Ron Bob, as he is known up on Ridge Road, doesn't like O/Us of any kind. I think it's because he can't get a double without 4 or 5 shells, but don't tell him I told you.

12 gauge with 4140 chrome moly-steel 28" barrels, weighing only 5.9 lbs
Barrels are chrome plated inside & outside with a blued finish

title: For Sale/Trade:  TZ 99 South African P226 clone
postcontent:
Looking to sell or trade my Tressitu TZ99. Mainly looking to trade it for something a bit smaller and concealable. Looking to do a straight across trade. This gun is simply awesome. It's accurate and consistent, it's just too big for me to carry around. For those of you know aren't aware of what this is, it's basically a Sig P226 clone. These were originally made by CZ (not the Czech company) in Serbia, but the Serbian company was eventually shut down. Two companies then proceeded to buy their equipment and their guns. Israel and South Africa. What I have was made in South Africa, and was one of the primary handguns issued to both South African police and their military. It's great for a shooter, truck gun, home defense, or whatever you may need it for, not only that it's still used by some police forces around the world today, such as: Israel, Bosnia, Serbia, Iraq, Macedonia, Montenegro and Jordan. It's a rare and inexpensive piece of not only fine machinery but also history, it was even used by some of the guys on Top Shot where you can see it's proven accuracy in action. This beast has an all stainless steel slide, sights and barrel, accompanied by a durable aluminium frame. It will come with 3 15rd original magazines.

http://topshotonhistory.wikia.com/wiki/TZ99

Barrel and lockplate does have some pitting and hammer does not release once cocked and trigger pulled. Nice finish still on wood stock. Own a piece of US history for the 150th anniversary of the Surrender at Appomattox.
